It looks like it's going to be a fairly close call. It looks like for the month of January, sugar will be down, dairy probably down overall, meat possibly slightly up overall, vegetable oils probably down, and cereals pretty similar to Dec. So overall, the change is fairly small. It would take me a very long time to calculate what I think the outcome will be, but I still suspect it will be under 135.0.

Currently 132, and little news about it being likely to rise. Volatility seems to be in the low single digits most months. 9 months of steady declines... last 4 years the dec->jan trend has been irregular. Anything that would have made news in January would have already happened...
December in at 132.4, decline continues.
Demand pressures are declining as well as the oil price stabilization.
132.4 - down trend continues.
https://twitter.com/macroalf/status/1610631402269057024
The trend is downward, so I'll put more weight on bin 2, but it's almost down to the noise whether it'll be above or below 135. But, the index has been monotonically declining since March 2022.
In looking at the monthly trends over the last few years, I think the index will rise from December 2022, but not skyrocket as it did at the beginning of 2022.
135.7. Fairly flat last few months, but trend in prices seem to be easing. Itâ€™s so close to the 135 boundary it could go either side.

The Nov value was already released, ahead of schedule, apparently 5 days ago: 135.7, down 0.2 from Oct's value. In recent months, the index has had a very gently declining trend, and I don't see why that won't likely continue. There are 2 more months of data left in the forecast. At this point, I think it's a toss-up between bins 2 and 3. With a decline of 0.3 in total over the past 2 months, bin 3 perhaps looks very slightly more likely.
Fairly steady, gradual decline the last 5 months, one assumes current pressures on the food supply chain (Ukranian war, Chinese zero-ish covid policies) are priced in.
federal reserve plays around with best narratives for political outcomes
135.9 for Oct. Holding steady the last couple of months.

The FFPI was at 135.9 for October, down 0.1 ("virtually unchanged") from September. So, it seems that the decline is largely over and that the index has leveled off. With 3 more months to go to January, a large move away from bin 2 or 3 seems unlikely and would require a large shock. I think prices are likely to go up a bit in winter, so I think bin 3 is most likely, with bin 2 slightly less likely.
Updating w/ September index: mixed; lower for meats and oils, higher for cereals. Let's see how this EU winter will impact world trade.

The FPI continued to decline in September 2022 to 136.3, but the decline is starting to level out. Four more months to go in the forecast. Large swings are possible, but I suspect that the index will end up somewhere around the 130-140 range in Jan 2023. I don't think prices will fall below 125, and barring some new disaster, I also don't think it's likely they'll rise to over 145. (At the moment, the crowd thinks there's a 26% chance they'll be over 155 and a 53% chance they'll be >=145.)
Trend analysis, potential impact from global saber-rattling.

Barring some new catastrophe on the scale of Russia's invasion of Ukraine, I can't picture the index moving over 160. It has come down and is more or less now resuming its pre-Ukraine trend. The question is whether that trend has peaked or not. I think somewhere in the 125-155 range is most likely. I don't think a value less than 125 is likely because fertilizer prices are still so high. But it's possible.
It looks like more grain and oil seed rape have been planted this year, probably because prices looked good, so supply is not quite as bad as expected, and so prices are calming off.
Updating w/ August index: mixed but mostly in-line, only cereals higher than my forecast, which is interesting.
Big drop in July mainly due to cereals price drops. I guess people have pre bought now and know where the risks are so prices have eased off.
Shifting my forecast further downward with June's result of 140.9.
Updating w/ July index: that was a massive drop... meat, dairy, and sugar still aligned with my forecasts, but had to adjust for cereals and oils.
The index has been coming down for the last few months from the Feb peak of 159

It looks like veg oils and cereals, which have been the major forces driving the index higher, are continuing to come down from their recent highs. I'm not sure whether they might go back up, especially grains. So I'll keep my forecast broad for now, centered around a prediction of a slightly lower value than now. Given the volatility of this index and of current events, I think the crowd's forecast may currently be too focused on the 155-165 bin.

Updating w/ June index: dairy came much higher and veg oils much lower than my forecast. I wouldn't expect this dairy trend to change as fast as other sectors, like what happened with veg oils, but it seems that cereals are already lower than what's in the index, the same for sugar. I'm lowering my range for Jan/23.
Updating with May index: meat and cereals higher, dairy and oils lower, sugar flat, but I was surprised with dairy downturn. My forecast falls between 145-155, but now on the lower end.

Interesting: half of all forecasters think that food prices are going down from here, despite the fertilizer shortage, palm oil exports from Indonesia being banned, wheat export bans from Russia, Ukraine, Serbia, Hungary, and India and increasing energy/transport prices. I'm reading forecasts of 2H2022 Global Famine way too frequently to believe things are getting cheaper from here. Is anyone else reading about the famine in Sri Lanka?

April update of FAO's Food Index came lower than my projection (-4%), with meat -2%, dairy -2%, cereals 0%, oils -9% (miss), and sugar +6% (beat), so some adjustments on my forecast were necessary, especially for:- oils: I expected prices to remain higher for longer, this correction surprised me, I need to do a deep dive on this- sugar: I was already expecting lower prices as harvest is underway in Brazil, but also due to a changing perception that SnD should be better than expected this year with Thailand and India increasing exportsAfter adjusting all variables, my forecast lowered to 148.9 (149.9 previous).

In the short term, (i) concerns over wheat exports from Russia and Ukraine should support cereal prices; (ii) higher fertilizer prices could negatively impact the level of technology used on most crops and should affect the world's SnD, especially for corn and soybeans; (iii) protective measures from some governments should also help sustain a higher reference, sensitive for oils; (iv) meat prices should continue to go up due to avian flu in the US and higher pork prices in the EU, US, and China; (v) with higher grain prices, I'd expect dairy prices uptrend to continue in the following months. Still broadly distributed, but shifting whole curve up on large MoM jump...
New print for March 2022 is 159.3. Two maxes in a row, with the highest MoM increase on record.

159 for March 2022, up 19 points likely due to Ukraine war. While food costs may come down in nominal terms after the conflict resolves, I see continued inflation so I expect food prices to continue to rise in real terms.

Starting with fairly broad distribution. The current increase seems likely to be persistent at current or higher levels (i.e. I'm at a roughly 78% or better chance that the index is >= current level upon resolution date). I'm currently higher than crowd on the extreme upward bins...hard to put a finger on exactly why, but I think that the compounding/overlapping effects of fertilizer shortages, war, general inflationary pressure, and ongoing drought and climate disruptions to global food production could catapult food prices into the stratosphere.

I predict that in January 2023 the Food Price Index will be up 10 points from where it is now. I did some modeling is not complete yet (https://app.datacamp.com/workspace/w/9cef92f2-009c-4572-b17e-b5db07bea220), so this is a preliminary prediction.

Food and energy are the most volatile commodities in the CPI. Food can go down even during highly inflationary periods, and considering the 24% rise in 2021 it is not certain that it will continue to rise even though I am convinced that inflation in general will remain high pretty much everywhere, the US, the EU, Russia, Japan, etc. Food would have to decline in price pretty severely to fall in price in nominal terms amid 8% general inflation.

This is a tough question. I expect the FFPI to go above 150 in the short term, but what happens after that depends on a lot of factors, including the farming situation in Ukraine (planting/fertilizing/harvesting/shipping) and Russia (how much exports?), on top of all of the ongoing pandemic disruptions, routine vagaries of the weather, and climate change. I expect pandemic dislocations to continue, as the pandemic continues to affect people all over the world, and as people's purchasing preferences seem to have shifted, for at least the medium term and perhaps the long-term future. But I'm not sure what's going to happen in Ukraine. And it's not just Ukrainian crops that cam be affected, it's trade with Ukraine and Russia, including fertilizer exports. I don't expect sanctions to be lifted this year, as I don't expect the conditions necessary for them to be lifted to be met. So, I'm relatively pessimistic about this question, where I define "pessimistic" to refer to anything over 120, which is bad enough. Also, I'll note that when the FFPI spiked in 2011, it remained elevated for several years. All that said, there can be incredible volatility in this index, so for many reasons, I'm casting a fairly wide net.
